It doesn‚Äôt just translate words to another language but also pictures you take on the spot or from gallery (just them offering gallery pics to translate is a HUGE PLUS), they also have a feature that has one part on one side of phone/device for one person to say something and the the other end of phone for the other person this makes allot more simple and this way you don‚Äôt necessarily have to take the time passing the phone back and forth (which works too ofc and is still simple but this just adds more efficiency), it keeps back and forth text history between the translation and translation history because we might just find our self in a situation where we didn‚Äôt remember everything that was said so we wanna go back in a conversation, but also don‚Äôt want to take another 20 minutes talking to somebody about the same thing we just spoke to them about just trying to figure out what the last thing was said or they might not be present anymore so this truly helps, also you can clear that history if you don‚Äôt want to keep it there, then there‚Äôs the Favorites section where you can favorite translations like a quote you like to say allot but you‚Äôre in a different speaking country and still want to say it. Dear Apple Care Team,
 
I hope this email finds you well. I am writing to express my concerns regarding a recent decision that denied a warranty repair request for my MacBook, and I am seeking a reconsideration of this decision.
 
My MacBook (Serial Number: FVFG37V0Q05D) and is well within its warranty period. However, I was informed that my warranty claim has been denied on the basis of three missing screws from inside the MacBook. I believe it is important to clarify the situation and address the denial of my warranty claim.
As there is history attached to my MacBook being repaired by your authorized service center and I request to kindly review all the repairing/service history from the Day 1 before coming to any conclusion.
 
To the best of my knowledge, I have not tampered with or opened the MacBook in any way that would lead to the removal of these screws. I have always used the MacBook under normal operating conditions, and I am surprised to hear that missing screws from inside the device are not covered under warranty. This is a human error as I mentioned it has been repaired earlier and there are highly chance that engineer might missed to install the three remaining screws.
 
I understand that the terms and conditions of warranties are in place to ensure fair usage, but I genuinely believe that the missing screws are not a result of any actions on my part. It is important to note that I have taken excellent care of my MacBook, and this issue has arisen without any external interference.
 
I kindly request that you reconsider my warranty claim and review the case thoroughly and provide me evidence which includes the CCTV footages. By saying that we have did an internal investigation and this cannot be repaired under warranty. This statement does not satisfy me, if you are not at fault show me the supporting documentation/evidence.
 
 
I value the trust I have placed in Apple as a brand and have always been a loyal customer. I hope that this situation can be resolved to my satisfaction, and I can continue to rely on Apple's commitment to customer service.
 
I look forward to your prompt response and a positive resolution to this matter. Please let me know the next steps or any additional information you may require reconsidering my case.
 
Thank you for your attention to this issue.

column9: Best quality translations available; one major flaw
column10:
The quality of translation that this app produces is probably the best available. It blows Google Translate out of the water. I say this because I use it to communicate with people in multiple other languages on a daily basis, and when I used Google translate they always knew I was using the translator, but when I started using apples native translator app, they all commented on how great it was. So native speakers were telling me that the quality of the translations was impeccable.of course it doesn't have as many languages it is Google translate, although it is expanding with each update. But that's not really a big deal because the languages they have available are the primary ones people will use in day-to-day conversation.

However, there is one serious flaw in this app. Using the integrated translation feature, meaning using it from within another app without having to switch over to the Translator app, about 60 to 70% of the time, the first time I select text and attempt to translate, or to change languages, I get an error that says translation is unavailable. It always works the next time I use it, so it's only a one time thing. but still it happens that first time 60 to 70% of the time that I use the integrated translation function. I've read all the tutorials and all the Support articles about how to possibly fix it, but nothing works. It's just a flaw in the app and Apple really needs to fix this quickly. Fixing this functionality should be a high priority, even more than expanding the number of languages they have available. my rating were only based on quality of translation this would easily be a five star app. But I can't give it more than three stars with this serious flaw

column9: Google translate was better than this
column10:
Usage of this app is extremely uncomfortable. First off, when translating from English to languages that use complex characters, like ‰∏≠Êñá (zhong wen) the written english pronuancation of the characters is not shown above or underneath the translated characters. Rather you have to click on each individual character to get the dictionary for that single character (clicking on something to get the dictionary only works in the outputed language). In addition, there is no option to immediately switch between the inputed and outputed languages. So when you have to manually change the languages, everything you wrote disappears. This is incredibly annoying if you are studying a language because you cannot see the definition for a character you inputed, since clicking on something to get the dictionary only works in the outputed language. Also, there is only 18 langauges you can choose from. So if you happen to be travelling to India for exmaple, your screwed. The only postive thing I can say about this app is the camera translation. 0 star

Edit: It turns out, to automatically switch languages you just click language for the input (will have blue dot). To get the dictionary for the input you have to press the dictionary button then the input. It took me hours of usage to finally realize that.

It is still fusterating that the english pronuanction is not shown underneath translated characters and the amount of languages are still limited.

After a while of trying to use this with studying Spanish I started getting suspicious and started double checking everything with SpanishDict. To put it nicely at best the translations are obscure or secondary (or tertiary). Nada bueno. Just one recent example: I was just listening to a song with the phrase ‚Äúno te fallo‚Äù. I looked it up on Translate and it said ‚ÄúI won‚Äôt let you‚Äù. Well that was not convincing grammatically for in the context of the song. SpanishDict results gave me ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt fail you‚Äù. Yup, that fits. I was going to rate two stars but really what is the point of having a translate app you can‚Äôt trust. Extra disappointing since it‚Äôs Apple‚Äôs stock translate app. I would rather prefer using native apps‚Ä¶ as long as they were arguably the best - or even worked! Disappointingly, unlike the Google translate app, there is not even a place for suggesting corrections, reporting errors, or any community input, nor are there any possible alternative meanings/ results suggested (in case of multiple possible meanings or in cases when it might be wrong).

column9: App makes me hate the Iphone
column10: Never seen a worse app in my entire life. Makes me want to not use Iphone just because this app exists.

When the app works, it is actually pretty good. The integration with iOS is nice, and the quality of translations, even offline ones, is pretty good. 

But, the offline (on-device) mode has some serious problems. It used to work most of the time, but there has always been a problem where it insists on re-downloading the dictionaries. Now, it has recently decided that it can only download one dictionary. Attempting to download a second results in the first being deleted, and there‚Äôs never a point where it actually functions correctly. 

Even when it used to function, it would demand downloading a new copy of the dictionary at inconvenient times. Do you want to right click on some text for a web page or in an email and translate it? Great. One time. The second time, it demands downloading the dictionaries again. And it does this over and over so that the app is essentially unusable offline (which is where I value it the most).

Finally, the support link on the store page is a joke. It just takes you to Apple‚Äôs generic support page for its devices. Nothing about the Translate app at all. No place to file a bug report. No place to seek assistance for it.

This app should be great. When it works, it is great, but it‚Äôs completely dropped the ball on the little things which are so vital to making it work consistently and, therefore, usefully. I guess it‚Äôs back to Google Translate until they fix this.

column9: Why keep it simple? Make it more useful!
column10:
I translate. Thus I have a need for learning the language. But after having translated my word, this App does not go further. Why not? 

Why not build from search that is available now to actually teaching the words that you have searched? Apply the method of Ask and Repeat in various ways for the searched words, until you can and know the word - and then the App moves on to new words.

Combine the previous with a database where all the words in a spesific language, starting with English, have been given an index (frequency) number based on how often the word is actually used in the language, say English. Yes, those kinds of listings actually exist, they are usually built upon observing radio programs, newspaper articles and books - and that‚Äôs in the old days. Nowadays internet is, of course, an infinite source for indexing vocabularies.

Anyways, teaching should be based on how frequently the words are used as more often used words are more useful. So add that capability to teaching. Ask more common words more often. Mix words that you have searched with words that are used frequently anyways and that you were not able to translate yourself when that word was quizzed by the App. Apply life style and professional preferences qiven by the user to give instructions to the App on what kinds of words to check and teach.

Maybe add a social dimension to this App then after the above. Spouses, friends, social media aquaintances could be doing the asking based on suggestions of the App. Etc, etc. The possibilities are endless.

Our world works better, when we understand each other better. Yes, machine translation will improve to something actually amazing, probably sooner than later. 

But learning a language yourself will always have material and intellectual value. 

So why keep this App stupid? What‚Äôs the business rationale?

column9: Bug that randomly does ‚ÄúTranslation not Available‚Äù
column10: (I only use this for Tap-and-hold on selected text) When network is slow, I have to put 2 seconds between taps, or it says ‚ÄúTranslation not available‚Äù. Fast menu tappers on slow networks will trigger a software race condition in this app, at least on iOS 15.2.1 especially if language autodetection algorithm executes network transmissions, and I keep tapping fast (e.g. select text, and tap ‚Äútranslate‚Äù faster than ping latency, etc). To make this app work merely semi-reliably, I have to intentionally slow down my screen taps to at least 2-3 seconds between taps, it‚Äôs ****ing annoying that the Apple developers haven‚Äôt discovered this bug, please run the Network Link Conditioner in xcode (test an erraticslly slow-fast-slow-fast link on a midrange A13 or thereabouts) and pretend you‚Äôre a fast iPhone/iPad tapper. Also if autodetect prompts you to download a new language, and you cancel by accident, and try translating the same selected text again, it britually errors out instantly (doesn‚Äôt even try) even when repeating on the same selected text. Translate seems to become broken internally that forces me to de-select text, retype or reword text, reselect the text, and try translate again to replace my chat text to the foreign language ‚Äî in order to remove this app‚Äôs seeming race-condition / deadlock / etc behaviour. Very annoying for rapid fire chats. By the way that Apple managment has decided to let this app languish at 2-star rating, it seems to imply that the Apple PM seems to dismiss all these ‚ÄúTranslation not Available‚Äù errors as user fault when it‚Äôs clearly poor sloppy intern programming logic in this app. Very buggy caching system that frequently forgets the second language downloaded, or fails if a download was interrupted partway / cancelled. This 2-star app could have been easily 4-star with minor bug fixes and proper poor-cellphone-network testing. Such simple bugfixes seemingly ignored by Apple management giving up on this app. It is as if this app has a weird quick-giveupper 250 millisecond timeout. Barf.

I tried this app a long time ago, hated it, and switched to Google Translate.  GT isn‚Äôt perfect, so today I tried this app, to see if improvements had been made that might be more useful to me.

Can you easily change which language you‚Äôre translating to and from? No!  This app only gives you drop boxes.  So, if I‚Äôm set up to translate from Spanish to English, but for this situation I want to translate from English to Spanish, I have to change the first drop down to English, then the second drop down to Spanish.  When I want to go back my original setup, I have to use the drop downs again. It‚Äôs a lot more taps than if the developers simply installed a switch button.

I do like the voice translation option where I can hold my phone out and I can read things in English, while the person across from me can read the language that the app is translating to. That could be very helpful in travel situations.  However, that‚Äôs not particularly useful when I am studying and need translation help.

All recents get saved to Favorites, which is awkward.  I would like a dedicated tab for Recents, while Favorites are, you know, the ones I have actually marked as Favorite. 

The font is super large, and bold, which makes translations look cartoonish and not great for longer sentences. There may be a way to change this, but trying to find my way around this clunky app was frustrating, so I didn‚Äôt look into it too deeply.

There may be features that I would like, but the user interface is so annoying that I don‚Äôt want to try and figure out what all the features are!

column9: Difference between Recognizing and Understanding My Voice
column10:
Two stars for basic ‚Äòease‚Äô of use - if only typing simple phrases for translation.
The reality is - the most common use of language on a day-to-day, person-to-person basis is the spoken language. 
Apple products (namely Siri) have difficulty understanding the human voice when speaking English much less a nonnative language. Quite frustrating. It‚Äôs not just me. It seems to be a widespread reality. Siri is better at recognizing my voice versus say the blender. (And that, not always.) Understanding and distinguishing words is another realm beyond Siri. 
To date, any app within the Apple environment that uses or especially requires Siri is going to sadly fall well short of any expectations.

This alone is what makes it a great alternative because Google freely steals an alarming amount of user data, in return for a ‚Äòbetter‚Äô experience. All translations made on Apple Translate are completed on device which makes it very secure. Speaking of translations, they are very fast and accurate, which is great. The selection of languages is also good, but it does miss quite a few. However, this isn‚Äôt something to concern yourselves about because Apple will inevitably add all languages in the foreseeable future. Overall, I strongly believe that more users should start using Apple Translate as their main translation app!

I was excited to try this app out for the first time. Since it is an Apple app, I figured it would have a clean UI that was straightforward and also offered some measure of privacy as compared to other translation apps. Boy, was I disappointed. The UI is not intuitive at all.

The UI on first impression is about what you would expect - two drop down boxes for language selection plus an input field to supply the text to be translated. And initially, everything seems to work as expected. But after a few seconds of using it, it becomes a frustration. 

Want to change the language selection of the search you just did by simply selecting a different language from the drop-down menus (you know, like on most other, simple-to-use translation apps)? Well, it seems you can‚Äôt do that. Even though the menus do indeed drop down and appear to allow you to make a different selection, the selection doesn‚Äôt ‚Äútake‚Äù and keeps reverting back to the original language selected. 

After many tries to see what would work, I gave up and concluded either there was no way to do this or if there is it is too unintuitive to discover. Instead, I ended up having to start a whole new search query from scratch even though I was translating the same original phrase. 

Also, the UI on my iPad looks like it was designed for an iPhone screen and simply blown up in size. This makes interacting with the elements cumbersome and unwieldy.

This could be a perfectly fine app as I do like the overall simplicity of the UI. But actually using it and interacting with it turns out to be an unexpected frustration and disappointment.
